al activity, his obligations to his sources, the cultural context, and the place of La Villa in Renaissance villa literature. It also demonstrates the enduring relevance of La Villa for architecture and landscape architecture. La Villa makes a valuable contribution to the body of literature about place-making, precisely because it treats the villa as an idea and not as a building type.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aGarden History. 7aARCHITECTURE / Landscape.2bisacsh  aArchitecture.  aFine Art.  aGarden History.1 aBeck, Thomas E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package World Historyz978311041347208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220380640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812203806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812203806.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041347-2  Penn Press eBook Package World History  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK